{"cursor":"13841","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/9/93/Mokats_Mirza.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox clergy\n| name = Komitas Vardapet image = Komitas 1902.jpg image_size = caption =\n| Komitas in Ejmiatsin, 1902 birth_date = 1869 nationality = Armenian\n| birth_place = KÃ¼tahya, Vilayet of Brusa, Ottoman Empire death_date = October\n| 22, death_place = Paris, France church = Armenian Apostolic Church other_names\n| = Soghomon Gevorgi Soghomonyan education = Etchmiadzin Seminary, Kaiser\n| Friedrich Wilhelm University ordained = 1893 writings = congregations =\n| offices_held = title = Vardapet (Archimandrite - celibate priest) spouse =\n| children = parents = footnotes =\n}}\n\n\n\n'Soghomon Gevorgi Soghomonyan' (), commonly known as 'Komitas Vardapet' (, by\nWestern Armenian transliteration also 'Gomidas Vartabed') or simply 'Komitas'\n('Gomidas') (born on September 26 or October 8, 1869, in KÃ¼tahya, Ottoman\nEmpire; died on October 22, 1935, in Paris, France) was an Armenian priest,\ncomposer, choir leader, singer, music ethnologist, music pedagogue and\nmusicologist. Many regard him as the founder of modern Armenian classical music.\n\nKomitas had a psychotic breakdown after witnessing the horrors of 1915\nArmenian Genocide and is considered a martyr of the Genocide. Soulahian\nKuyumjian, Rita. Archeology of Madness: Komitas, Portrait of an Armenian Icon.\nEdition: 2, Reading, England: Taderon Press; Princeton, NJ: Gomidas Institute,\n2001, p. 3.\n","linknr":285,"url":"Komitas_Vardapet","recorded":1374522765,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Komitas_Vardapet&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Komitas_Vardapet&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2